            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Alexei Orlov\u2019s journey to San Francisco was a flight from a collapsing world. Born in Leningrad in 1970, his youth was steeped in the rigid certainty of the Soviet Union. When the union fractured, so did his future. With a basic high school education and few prospects, he followed a distant aunt\u2019s sponsorship to San Francisco in the mid-90s, arriving with a thin wallet and an even thinner grasp of English.\n\nThe city\u2019s chaotic freedom was both intoxicating and terrifying. Alexei found work in construction and restaurant kitchens, his strong back his only real asset. The cultural chasm and profound loneliness, however, took their toll. He found a false friend in vodka, a ghost from his homeland that slowly consumed his new life. For over a decade, he drifted through a haze of lost jobs, strained relationships, and the constant threat of homelessness, a man invisible in a bustling city.\n\nThe turning point came not as a single event, but as a slow, painful crawl from rock bottom. A health crisis landed him in a public clinic in the Tenderloin, where a compassionate social worker saw past the broken man to the survivor within. It was there he was introduced to recovery programs. The process was grueling, but in the shared stories of others, Alexei finally felt understood. He realized his deepest shame\u2014his experience with addiction\u2014was also his greatest strength.\n\nHe earned his certification as a Peer Recovery Coach, dedicating his life to the work that saved him. Now, at 53, Alexei\u2019s days are structured and purposeful. He lives in a small, tidy apartment in the Inner Richmond, a neighborhood that reminds him of the old world with its fog and tight-knit community feel. Each morning, he takes the 38-Geary bus 6.5 miles downtown to the nonprofit where he works. There, he offers guidance, empathy, and the hard-won wisdom of his own journey to people struggling with the same demons he once faced. His income is modest, but his life is rich with meaning. His dream is no longer about personal gain, but about witnessing one more person find their footing. San Francisco, the city that nearly broke him, has become the city he helps heal, one person at a time."
